{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638898"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.95,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"7871"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24413"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24415"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with fatigue and pallor over the past month. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a vegetarian and reports heavy menstrual periods. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Laboratory investigations reveal anaemia with a low mean corpuscular volume of 70 fL (80-100).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a potential cause of the patient\u0027s anaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitamin B12 deficiency","Iron deficiency","Folate deficiency","Chronic kidney disease","Hypothyroidism"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with microcytic anaemia, as indicated by the low mean corpuscular volume. The most common cause of microcytic anaemia is \u003Cstrong\u003Eiron deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E, which is consistent with her vegetarian diet and heavy menstrual periods. Iron deficiency leads to reduced haemoglobin production, resulting in smaller red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E causes macrocytic anaemia, characterised by a high mean corpuscular volume, due to impaired DNA synthesis in red blood cell precursors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolate deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E also leads to macrocytic anaemia, similar to vitamin B12 deficiency, and is not associated with a low mean corpuscular volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause normocytic anaemia due to reduced erythropoietin production, but it does not typically result in microcytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause normocytic or macrocytic anaemia, but it is not a common cause of microcytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Microcytic anaemia is characterised by a low mean corpuscular volume and is commonly caused by iron deficiency.","Vitamin B12 deficiency typically causes macrocytic anaemia"],"references":["Rampon K. Anemia: Microcytic Anemia. FP Essent. 2023 Jul;530:12-16. PMID: 37390396.","Miller JL. Iron deficiency anemia: a common and curable disease. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2013 Jul 1;3(7):a011866. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a011866. PMID: 23613366; PMCID: PMC3685880.","Kumar A, Sharma E, Marley A, Samaan MA, Brookes MJ. Iron deficiency anaemia: pathophysiology, assessment, practical management. BMJ Open Gastroenterol. 2022 Jan;9(1):e000759. doi: 10.1136/bmjgast-2021-000759. PMID: 34996762; PMCID: PMC8744124."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60408"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T09:54:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T09:54:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type